{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607440"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:22:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:22:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15958"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110234"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92505"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8599"},{"type":"tags","id":"8603"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110234"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the ectoderm germ layer gives rise to both epidermis and neural tissue. The fate of ectodermal cells depends on specific molecular signals present during gastrulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of bone morphogenetic proteins in ectodermal development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suppresses all ectodermal differentiation","Maintains ectodermal stem cell state","Induces mesodermal development","Promotes epidermal differentiation","Stimulates neural tissue formation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring gastrulation, \u003Cstrong\u003Epromotes epidermal differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary role of bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs) in ectodermal development. In the absence of BMP signalling, ectoderm naturally develops into neural tissue via the default neural pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses all ectodermal differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E - BMPs specifically promote epidermal differentiation while inhibiting neural fate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains ectodermal stem cell state\u003C/strong\u003E - Rather than maintaining stemness, BMPs actively drive differentiation towards epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduces mesodermal development\u003C/strong\u003E - While BMPs contribute to mesoderm formation, their key role in ectoderm is promoting epidermal fate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates neural tissue formation\u003C/strong\u003E - BMPs suppress neural development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe BMP antagonists noggin and chordin block BMP signalling in specific regions, allowing neural tissue to develop where these inhibitors are present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bone morphogenetic proteins promote formation of epidermis from ectoderm during gastrulation.","The default fate of ectoderm is neural tissue unless influenced by specific signalling molecules.","Noggin and chordin antagonise bone morphogenetic proteins to allow neural tissue formation."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92505"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15958"}},